4 HJR___ COMMENDING DR. LEON FRAZIER ON HIS ACCOMPLISHMENTS.
5
6 WHEREAS, with great pride and special reverence, we
7 commend Dr. Leon Frazier for his many accomplishments; and
8 WHEREAS, he loved people genuinely and served others
9 selflessly and his departure leaves a void in the lives of
10 his loving family, many friends, and the community where he
11 was highly regarded; and
12 WHEREAS, Dr. Frazier was born on May 16, 1932; from a
13 young age he pursued education, and it became a cornerstone
14 of his life; he earned a Bachelor of Science in Education
15 from South Carolina State College, a Master of Science in
16 Guidance and Counseling from Alabama A&M University, and a
17 Doctor of Education in Educational Psychology from Oklahoma
18 State University; he completed further graduate study in
19 Public Administration at the University of Oklahoma; and
20 WHEREAS, Dr. Frazier's professional career includes
21 noted experience as a public school teacher in South
22 Carolina; civilian technical training instructor at the
23 United States Air Force Electronics Training Center in
24 Biloxi, Mississippi; and Technical Instructor Supervisor and
25 Education Specialist, respectively, at the United States
26 Army Missile School at Redstone Arsenal; and
27 WHEREAS, Dr. Frazier served in many capacities in
28 higher education as a professor, vice president, and in the
Page 1

higher education as a professor, vice president, and in the
HJR33 INTRODUCED
29 Office of Student Affairs at Oklahoma State University and
30 Alabama A&M University; he also served as a Licensed
31 Psychologist for the State of Alabama and State Commissioner
32 of the Alabama Department of Pensions and Security; and
33 WHEREAS, he held positions of leadership with a
34 number of public service organizations, including board
35 president of the American Institute of Psychotherapy
36 Graduate School of Psychology; president of the National
37 Association of College Deans, Registrars, and Admissions
38 Officers; and member of the Governor's Advisory Council on
39 Humanitarian Services; in addition, he was a member of the
40 job development subcommittee of the Alabama Development
41 Commission and many other organizations and committees
42 serving the community in meaningful ways; and
43 WHEREAS, Dr. Frazier's faith-based leadership
44 activities included serving as the Jurisdictional Executive
45 Secretary and Finance Officer of Church of God in Christ,
46 Alabama Second Jurisdiction; and Jurisdictional President of
47 the youth department for 23 years; Dr. Frazier was Project
48 Director for the founding and accreditation of the Apostolic
49 School of Ministry of North Alabama; he provided counsel to
50 many faith-based projects of churches in the Southeastern
51 United States; and
52 WHEREAS, Dr. Frazier was regarded highly in the
53 communities where he resided and served; most notably are
54 the schools that are named in his honor, including the
55 Harris Home for Children and Frazier Preparatory School in
56 Uganda, which has three campuses; and
Page 2

Uganda, which has three campuses; and
HJR33 INTRODUCED
57 WHEREAS, Dr. Frazier is preceded in death by his
58 wife, Irlene Sharperson Frazier; together they reared three
59 children, all of whom earned college degrees; now therefore,
60 BE IT RESOLVED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA, BOTH
61 HOUSES THEREOF CONCURRING, That we warmly commend Dr. Leon
62 Frazier for his many distinguished accomplishments, and we
63 hereby dedicate this resolution to him posthumously with
64 utmost appreciation, admiration, and regard.
